I only got in one game of edh at SCG. I immediately realized that my "play for fun" was at a higher level than the others, one of them being new to commander, so I started to pull punches with Tuvasa.
This led to me eventually losing by a hair. But it was worth it.

<@UGK9N4JJ2> I think Sevinne does well as a token build. "when you cast instant or sorcery, get XYZ token" and swarm. But as the games went, it was mostly just removal until I had enough fliers to wham
But then, why not play Kykar?
There was only one pay off for casting from the yard, the Spirit maker
None of the others care, young pyro, kykar himself, the monk maker, the blue one from RAV... They don't even benefit from the doubled spells from Sevinne, so... Who cares?

So the reason to play Sevinne over Kykar seems a bit odd at first. 

Kykar is the most obvious choice as he says it right on the card. That being said, if you are using Kykar to make tokens, and not combo off, he is much more fragile, as you need to hope he doesn’t die multiple turns in a row. Kykar makes you spirits that you can use to ramp, and that is also super strong when you’re a mana or two short. He has pros and cons.

Sevinne on the other hand allows you to eek out small incremental advantages throughout the game, while being much harder to get rid of. He also does a much better job at chump blocking than Kykar’s spirits do. He comes down on 5, has a lower chance of dying, and rewards you for something you already want to do; cast a bunch of spells. In his case though, you aren’t casting haymakers, you’re playing spells that get you small advantages over time, that he just compounds. 

The best way to look at it is Kykar is the most “efficient” commander for Jeskai tokens. He does the thing, no questions asked. He makes tokens, and rewards you. Sevinne greases the wheels, and allows you to keep up your incremental advantages,  while also moving your game plan forward and being more resilient to removal.

I had my board wipes twice in a game with Sevinne, and I could easily recover because I wasn’t just casting a Think Twice or a Deep Analysis once, but essentially three times when Sevinne was out. I was able to revive faster and me more resilient than Kykar could be.
It’s more of an argument of efficiency vs resiliency, and I’d rather be a resilient token deck in EDH, but I’m also a super careful player.

Maybe it's a meta thing, but I don't think Sevinne is all that resilient, outside of a good blocker. Most of the removal you'll deal with isn't damage based, it's destroy or exile. Sure, you can have counters for that sort of thing, but so can Kykar, who even benefits from getting more bodies and/or mana from casting those counters. With that being said, I will say for the sake of the precons, they were somewhat light in removal, or at least from the few games I've played, that's how it's happened.
